28-year-old cook found dead in San Francisco shopping mall
The 28-year-old cook, who recently moved to San Francisco, was found dead in a flight of stairs at a local mall this week.
However, the victim’s brother says that he cannot imagine anyone wanting to hurt him, noting: “At last his business was going smoothly.”
The body, found in Westfield Mall on Wednesday morning, was identified as 28-year-old San Francisco resident Frank Galicia, the San Francisco Bureau of Forensic Medicine said.
The San Francisco Police Department reports that the death was classified as a murder and the investigation is ongoing.
The victim’s brother, Luis Galizia, told ABC’s KGO in San Francisco that Frank, a past delivery line cook in Boston, got his dream job as a cook at San Francisco’s Sons & Daughters restaurant six months ago.
A Sons & Daughters spokesman said they were "shocked and devastated" by his death.
“We are a small team that works as a close-knit family and will be sorely missed,” the spokesperson said.
Our thoughts and condolences are with Frank’s family and friends during this difficult period.
Luis Galizia said Frank was staying at the hostels first, but more recently, "It's finally working out."
“He found an apartment, he was dating a girl,” Luis Galizia told KGO.
Luis Galizia said he could not imagine anyone wanting to hurt his younger brother.
He had a good heart and a great soul.
His way of connecting with his family has always been to cook us some dish, to cook us dinner,” said Luis Galizia.
He never wanted to be involved in a fight.
He was a brother who swam with the flow.
“For all the bad things that are happening to this world, it was the uncut diamond that shone brightly every day,” he said.
Anyone with information is asked to call the SFPD Hotline at 415-575-4444.
Churkin said that the meeting of the UN security Council on the Crimea was useful.
Permanent Representative of the Russian Federation to the UN Vitaly Churkin said that the last meeting of the UN Security Council on Crimea was useful, Interfax reports.
“I think the discussion was useful for us, and we provided them with information about what happened,” Churkin said.
