The next day, a newspaper described Mr. Erdogan’s actions as if nothing bad had ever happened.
I think his enthusiasm meant the opposite.
But the lingering coolness emanating from Mr Putin has shown that the Russian leader has not forgotten anything.
In fact, the cause of the crisis was the first thing he mentioned in the opening comments: Turkey shot down a Russian fighter jet on the Syrian border.
Moscow’s reaction at this point was furious.
Mr. Putin burst into an angry tirade, accusing Ankara of stabbing Moscow in the back.
The insult was even stronger, coming from an alleged friend.
Restoring real trust will be difficult, probably impossible.
Russian public opinion has also changed since November.
For months, state-controlled media carried out a stunning, all-out assault on Ankara.
Suddenly it seemed that the Turks should be considered guilty of everything.
The most serious were accusations from senior officials that Mr. Erdogan’s own family profited from the illegal oil trade from the areas of Syria controlled by the so-called Islamic State.
He denied it strongly.
But in St. Petersburg, there was an official signal that it was time to move on.
After all, this meeting only happened because Mr. Putin received the apology he demanded from President Erdogan.
Russia could claim victory of its own kind.
For Ankara, the benefits of a cease-fire are clear.
First and foremost, Erdogan needs all the friends he can get after he was nearly ousted from his post last month in a coup attempt.
Repeated terrorist attacks on Turkey have clearly shocked him, too.
There is also an economic reason.
Russian sanctions have hit hard — especially the ban on charter flights, which typically bring several million Russian tourists to the Turkish coast each year.
The number fell sharply by almost 90%.
As for Russia, tour operators and charter companies here will certainly feel relieved when the flights finally resume.
They put on the peak of the end of the season in the Mediterranean.
And even this week, state television predicted cheaper fruits and vegetables as soon as Turkish agricultural imports are allowed again.
"Tourists there, tomatoes back here," as the report in the Vedomosti newspaper put it.
But the visit also had additional political value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry at the West for what it sees as a weak response to the coup attempt.
Add to that her lingering dissatisfaction with the turtle-like pace of talk of joining the EU and Mr. Putin’s move — which seeks to take advantage of the cool and gradually erode Turkish ties with the West.
The Russian leader, of course, won bonus points with Ankara for calling for support for elected authorities after the coup attempt.
Keep in mind, this is a given for Moscow, which has its own deep-seated fear of regime change.
So, the summit at this brilliant palace on the seashore allowed Russia and Turkey to present what one analyst described to me as an “alliance of the bad”: two countries that feel rejected and humiliated by the West are joining forces.
Yet, despite the public display of reconciliation, the two still have significant differences.
The key is Syria, where Moscow has recently positioned itself as a peacemaker, but where Russia and Turkey support opposite sides.
