The HASSP system has been mandatory for catering for more than a year, but most cafes and restaurants in St. Petersburg have not yet implemented it.
Inspections are becoming more active, and the business faces fines of up to 1 million rubles.
For more than a year, Hazard Analysis and Critical Control Points (HACCP, in the Russian version of HACCP) - risk analysis and critical control points - are mandatory for use by food manufacturers and carriers, as well as catering companies in Russia, as a member of the Customs Union (CU).
Inspections of business by Rospotrebnadzor for compliance with these standards in St. Petersburg began in February 2015.
But so far, officials write fines only for certain violations of the regulations (see "List of documents" ...).
Failure to comply with the regulations as a whole will cost the company 600 thousand rubles for the first violation and 1 million rubles for the second.
HACCP as a system that takes into account risks when working with food and prevents them, was invented in the United States in the 1960s.
It was about the safety of food for astronauts.
Now the system is used in all food enterprises not only in the United States, but also in Canada and in the European Union.
Since February 2015, HACCP has been operating on the territory of the Customs Union.
For the development and implementation of the system, the business had 4 years (the HACCP requirement appeared in the technical regulations of the CU in 2011).
However, both entrepreneurs and officials admit that most companies have not even heard of this norm.
We, unfortunately, have long been sure that the norm applies only to food production, and not to restaurateurs,” explained Elena Tsereteli, head of the Public Council.
Now everyone is trying to catch up.
