The ultimate consumer of vinyl: who actually buys records?
Single middle-aged men love vinyl.
And until you rushed to litter the comments section with rude insults under the pseudonym NotAllLonelyMenMiddleyears, this statement follows from the actual data.
According to YouGov, so much of the discussed revival of records is due not to the boom among the generation of two thousand, who want to feel the novelty of the material object, but the nostalgia of middle years.
Those who have recently bought a vinyl album are more likely to be between the ages of 45 and 54, according to the data.
Moreover, those who belong to the age group of 18-24 years are the least likely.
It is also not just an act of gathering by amateurs - it has an emotional meaning: older vinyl buyers are slightly more likely to keep their feelings to themselves (56% vs. 53%) and enjoy loneliness (69% vs. 66%).
But are the results of YouGov true?
If this blog were a television news report, the camera would follow me as I walked down the middle of a busy Soho street, in a modest gray suit and gesticulating violently before stopping, folding my hands and saying something impressive like, "Okay, let's see."
Okay, let's see.
While Soho’s heart is slowly losing its charm and dirt — hotels, cafes, Paperchase shops have now flooded the buildings once occupied by independent sellers — several music stores with fantastic specialists still remain.
I would probably ask the camera to stop for the next scene, in which I am close to various people in some of these stores and trying to assess their age and emotional attitude through observation.
Glasgow-born Stewart, 55, followed by me from Sister Ray (counting data: two young women, three middle-aged men) to Reckless Records (counting data: eight middle-aged men, one woman probably over 20), in London for a half-day to hold a meeting, and strolling around the shops to take a few hours.
He's a collector, I ask?
"I suppose so," he says.
I have about 3,000 or 4,000 records.
These records, pictured above (he emailed me a picture, I didn't chase him home), line the walls of his living room.
His reason for acquiring so many albums and singles stems in part from his disposable income: he can now buy records he couldn’t afford when they first came out and buy back items he sold when he was young and broke.
"A lot of what I'm getting is the late '60s, early '70s, things that came out when I was 11 or 12, things that I was probably too young to buy for," he says.
He agrees that those who buy records are likely introverts who like their own company, adding, "I don't smoke, I don't drink very much.
That's my flaw.
Wez, 25, who works for Sister Ray, also believes that many of the clients he meets fit the profile of YouGov.
He noticed, however, a new wave of people who were under the influence of the media hype, people who heard about the return and felt the obligation to buy back their old records.
Judging by the conversations I had, people got rid of their collection, usually around 1998 or 1999.
Customers who once sold their vinyl to buy CDs are now selling their CDs to buy back their records,” he says.
This may explain the boom among vinyl revivalists of a certain age.
What about the supposed emotional importance of the records?
Spend a few seconds in a store like Phonica to understand that record stores offer a comfortable society to people with similar views.
According to Wes, some older customers, in particular, are insulted by the non-cash payment system.
Some vinyl lovers may feel overwhelmed by the digital world and prefer to retreat into the permanence of familiar record envelopes, items that evoke memories of a serene youth.
“I think sometimes it can be filling the void or having material things as a kind of comfort,” says Wes.
Since I am a collector myself, I have it, and I think a lot of people have it too.
It's an easy way to keep your head busy.
"We're like their social workers!" said a colleague from the record rack.
An ICM poll in April found that nearly 50% of people who bought a vinyl album last month had not yet listened to it.
The survey also found that 41% have a record player they never use, while 7% of those who buy vinyl have no record player.
At this point in the news report, I would probably look seriously puzzled by swiping through a stack of Bosanoff compilations.
The trophy aspect of rebirth is what Johnny, 42, who works at Sounds of the Universe (counting: three middle-aged men) has noticed.
“Someone came in recently and said, ‘I don’t have a record player, but I want to buy a Radiohead record so we can put it on our shelf,’” he says.
It’s not a big percentage, but it definitely happens.
More of the piece, less of the music.
We have people who say, "I don't have a record player."
These are younger people, not the elderly, they are a little under twenty, who are just getting acquainted with this.
Fopp, who has now taken almost the entire floor of vinyl, has a much more diverse audience when I arrive.
There are couples who are over 70, tourists who take pictures, teenage boys and middle-aged women.
Although the atmosphere is less laid-back than in the aforementioned stores — the latest synth and sexy-pop Wild Beast, rather than jazz improvisation, makes its way through the speakers — it’s nice to see the diversity in its customers.
None of them look particularly lonely, but agonizing psychological trauma is difficult to establish by standing for 30 seconds next to someone.
Eleanor, 27, walked on Fopp for a few minutes, reviewing various records available for sale.
She looks at the goods, not the money.
She does not earn much, she says, so collecting records is not a very suitable option.
It's expensive.
Listening to music on a computer or other device is simple, but the beauty of vinyl is...” she plunges into dreams with a sigh filled with love.
I don't know how to explain it - it's really unique.
My last stop is a store that is said to have contributed to the emergence of a new generation of vinyl lovers: Urban Fashionistas.
While I create the illusion that I'm looking at denim tight shorts, I'm watching a group of teenage girls gather around a Polaroid camera every minute before a father and his daughter discuss buying a Crosley player.
On the left is a staircase, the wall of which is set by Adele, Jeff Buckley, Amy Winehouse and Fleetwood Mack records: a mixture of modern style and classics, mandatory records for any medium collection.
No one is looking — perhaps because they are just a decoration, some are so high on the wall that it would be impossible to touch them.
It's real "artistic vinyl."
But given that any attention to these items could mean more money for the industry and send a few customers to the hinterlands of Soho for a while yet, there’s almost nothing to complain about.
Not surprisingly, the layer of the population that is more likely than most to have more time and money than most is the layer that spends most of the money on luxury items like vinyl.
But while my findings suggest that YouGov’s results are accurate, at least in SoHo record stores, they don’t rule out the existence of a huge number of women collectors and vinyl lovers who exist in reality, in record stores and on online forums.
These people probably work hard in schools or offices.
But they clearly don’t spend the morning of Thursday shopping on Berwick Street, flipping through records and avoiding the looks of an unpleasant 30-year-old fake host who hangs over the shoulders of unsuspecting middle-aged men.
