French court rejects proposal to demolish shops in Jungle refugee camp
A French court has rejected a proposal by Calais authorities to demolish dozens of makeshift shops and restaurants in the Jungle Camp, home to thousands of refugees.
At court hearings this week, Calais authorities said the state should be able to demolish a total of 72 makeshift shops where people inside the camp sell goods ranging from cigarettes to energy drinks, offer a haircut or sell tea for 50 cents (40p) or simple meals for a few euros in makeshift restaurants.
Kale Prefecture has said that these places should be demolished because they represent a parallel economy that does not pay taxes, and because they carry fire and sanitary risks.
Humanitarian groups have told the court that shops and restaurants are vital, saying the free meals offered by the pro-government association and other groups do not provide enough food for the growing camp population.
They have argued that home-made shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food to those in need.
Lille's court ruled there was no legal basis to kick out people running 72 home-made stores, but said the problems of Kale Prefecture "were fully understood."
Judge Jean-Francois Molla said groceries, cafes and restaurants played a much bigger role than simply feeding people who "live in extremely precarious conditions."
He said the spaces provided quiet meeting points for refugees and volunteers.
One of the places that was threatened with demolition was the Camp Jungle Book children's cafe, which works not for profit and offers 200 lunches a day, English and French classes, and shelter counseling for hundreds of vulnerable unaccompanied minors in the camp.
More than 170,000 people signed a petition to protect the children's cafe.
A letter sent to the Guardian said its closure "would be a disaster for these children, some of whom are under the age of eight."
