Britain stops at silver in rugby 7, after Fiji master class allows them to take gold
The UK's impressive series in Rugby 7 was crushed at the final hurdle by the Fiji team in the final on Thursday night, when they were completely defeated 43-7 at Deodoro Stadium here in Rio.
Fiji was given a master class in ball possession, evasiveness, game support, line running, and brute force to win gold, their first Olympic medal of any color.
The defeat came with not-so-poor consolation in the form of silver — Britain's third in a day — and they could be proud of their efforts in the first Olympic tournament in Rugby 7, in which they defeated New Zealand, Argentina and South Africa along the way.
The painful beating of the Boks, 7-5 in the semifinals earlier in the day, could return to negatively affect them in the finals.
But, in spite of everything, Fiji in this form won the best team of 15 people.
It may be some consolation for the UK — but probably not — that at least one Briton will hang a gold medal around his neck tomorrow: Fiji's head coach is Ben Ryan, a former England chief from Wimbledon.
It was a journey for Britain.
Eight years ago, under Ryan, they lost every game at the Adelaide Sevens.
They only lost one here.
These blows will hurt, but the progress is amazing.
Fiji started off great, for fun, beating off attempts by Great Britain to intercept the ball.
It was like bumping into a column of moving buses for Captain Tom Mitchell and the company, and the World Series champions went up 5-0 when Osea Colinisau dived into the corner.
With four minutes on the clock, Jerryr Tuway added another touchdown on the right flank, which was implemented.
12-0 and the UK barely touched the ball.
A magnificent attempt to intercept Mitchell kept Mount Leon Nakarava from scoring a third, but that only delayed Fiji.
In the seventh minute, Jas Veremalua made a touchdown in the right corner, and the UK lost 17-0.
Nakarava added another after resuming and the clock was still over a minute... in the first half.
Vatemo Ravovo then broke through several more sluggish attempts to intercept Britain and stormed the line to get a point.
The implementation resulted in a 29-0 break.
It looked as if Fiji had been born to play rugby 7, while the UK was still mastering the craft.
Which is pretty much what it is.
Great Britain made massive substitutions for half of the game, and they clogged the Fijian dam... for all four minutes, which was good by the standards of the first half until Joshua Tuisov passed after several brilliant Fijian interactions.
Dan Norton grabbed a try for the UK by making a touchdown in the left corner to score 36-7, but the game has long followed the path of the South Sea Islanders, whose fans sang, waved flags and danced in the stands.
It was impossible not to admire Fiji ' s joyous approach.
Mata William embellished a Fijian cake that did not need embellishment, another attempt in the last seconds.
The whistle sounded, the Fijians hugged, and the UK fell onto the lawn, completely defeated.
Earlier in the day, Fiji defeated Japan 20-5 in their semi-finals, and the UK slightly outscored South Africa in a tight one-try semi-final each — the difference being the British realisation.
Kyle Brown leads the Boks ahead in the first half, but Dan Norton, with some great leg work, tore the line and scored under the beams in the second half.
A brilliant last-ditch interception attempt from Marcus Watson, the 15-way brother of England's side, Anthony, secured the victory — and ultimately the silver medal.
Helen Glover and Heather Stanning are inspired to win the rowing fight coach with cancer
There will be no more thrilling gold at these games, and that says something.
From the first movement to the last, 220 heavy climbs in history, Helen Glover and Heather Stanning found the added value of their golden moment on Estacio da Lagoa.
Although they were the two who pulled the oars, there were three voices in this boat, the echo of coach Robin Williams was always there while they were aiming for the second consecutive Olympic gold in women's pairs, the first women in the annals of British sport to reach such a height.
Their superiority was absolute, after all it was their 39th undefeated performance, again unprecedented.
What we see is that two brilliant female athletes, gliding on the surface with the elegance of swans, do not fully reflect the nature of triumph.
Behind every gold rowing battalion of ready-made hands contributing to the incremental victories that are important, and there are no hands that were more important than the hands of a coach who 30 months ago, when he was diagnosed with cancer, did not know if he would live to see this day.
Like he said, it was a dangerous case.
I had bladder cancer, which is one of the things they can operate on, and they did.
If they don't, it goes everywhere.
It could have been a pretty bad situation.
It changes your views for the future a little bit.
Williams was diagnosed in December 2013.
The trio are fortunate to have been able to begin treatment in early 2014 in the off-season, keeping the schedule gap minimal if that can be the right expression in circumstances like these.
I needed to be paid, so I needed to get better quickly.
It was an incentive.
I was in the hospital and walking around the ward - 20 feet, 30 feet, 50 feet at a time, although they said it was enough a few steps.
That's how it starts.
Rowing itself is a journey, but it makes it a little more.
The next moment after the victory, their first thoughts were about Williams, who spent a nervous morning talking a little more than usual in an attempt to overcome his own experiences.
Stanning, a captain in an artillery regiment serving in Afghanistan, said: "I've been an emotional wreck this week, maybe a little too much, but it means so much."
It just confirms how much it means to me, how much Helen and I have worked, and so has Robin.
It's been a fantastic three years with Helen and Robin.
Without Robin, we would be nothing, so thank him very much, he is the best coach in the world.
I couldn’t ask for the best partner for training or the best coach.
Helen Glover and Heather Stanning have not lost a race in five years.
This pair sets a tense rhythm that their competitors could never match.
Even in the last 500 meters, when the teams of New Zealand and Denmark began to approach, Stanning and Glover had too much in reserve.
We were very much in phase.
Helen called out, 'Stay in the process, stay in the process.'
Now it is very important not to get carried away.
We had a good start and at the same time we weren’t trying to do something amazing.
We weren’t expecting fireworks today, we were just expecting to be able to row well and get out and win this race, which we did.
It will take a couple of years to decide their future.
Glover needs to be at the wedding next month, at her own with television adventurer Steve Backshall.
She just wants to enjoy the moment.
I didn’t want to say it was my last race.
That would mean too much pressure.
It took about six months in London to realize that I had become an Olympic champion.
It was all so new and I was so tense.
It took about four minutes here.
I feel so much better,” she said.
The government extended the term of destruction of sanctions products
The government has extended until the end of 2017 the deadline for the destruction of food products prohibited for import to Russia.
The relevant resolution was signed by Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev, it is published on the official portal of legal information.
The embargo against the countries that imposed anti-Russian sanctions because of the situation in Ukraine was introduced in our country in August 2014.
Subsequently, the ban has been repeatedly extended, now it is valid until December 31, 2017.
It is forbidden to import some types of agricultural products, raw materials and food from the USA, EU countries, Canada, Australia, Norway, Ukraine, Albania, Montenegro, Iceland and Liechtenstein.
In particular, meat and meat products, fish, seafood, vegetables, fruits and dairy products were banned.
Disposal of food imported into the country bypassing the embargo, held in Russia since August 2015.
In the first quarter of 2016 alone, about 100 tons of banned products were withdrawn from sale.
