The United Nations is investigating the use of chemical weapons in Syria.
A special UN commission is investigating the possible use of toxic gas in rebel-held areas of the Syrian city of Aleppo.
All parties to the conflict deny the use of chlorine, but the UN special envoy for Syria, Steffan de Mistura, believes the fact is undeniable.
Similar statements were made on the eve of the third round of intra-Syrian talks, which are scheduled to begin in late August in Geneva.
UN experts have launched an investigation into reports of the use of chemical weapons in the Syrian city of Aleppo.
The first information about the terrorist attack with the use of toxic gas, presumably chlorine, appeared on August 2.
Then the opposition said that in the area where the Russian military transport helicopter was shot down the day before, the aircraft dropped bombs with a poisonous substance, but in Moscow these accusations were called a throw-in.
Later, the Russian Defense Ministry accused the opposition group “Kharakat Nur al-Din al-Zinki” of the incident.
Soon it became known that there were two bombs filled with toxic gas.
This was confirmed by the BBC one of the victims.
“A few minutes later, I smelled gas, I started burning my eyes, it became difficult to breathe,” the eyewitness said.
As a result of the attack, at least 7 people were killed, 23 were hospitalized.
If the use of poison gas is confirmed by experts, the actions will be regarded as a war crime.
The UN special envoy for Syria, Staffan de Mistura, told reporters: “There is a lot of evidence that this really happened.”
The inadmissibility of the use of chlorine for military purposes is stipulated in the Convention on the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (CWC).
Despite the fact that all parties to the Syrian conflict deny the use of toxic gases, in 2015, human rights activists recorded 35 cases of chlorine use by the Syrian army against the “moderate opposition”.
The situation in Aleppo is complicated by the fact that shelling of its areas is carried out daily, and terrorists prevent the withdrawal of residents from the city.
According to Reuters, the UN expects Russia to establish a “humanitarian pause” in hostilities.
The current regime of a daily three-hour lull in the organization is considered “insufficient to help almost 2 million civilians trapped”.
Staffan de Mistura’s humanitarian adviser, Jan Egeland, said a 48-hour ceasefire would be needed every week to bring aid to the city and evacuate the sick and wounded.
“We have to send bulk cargo from the column of trucks in an area where the roads are almost destroyed, and those that remain are mined,” Mr. Egeland said.
Consultations in Geneva between representatives of the United States and Russia on the establishment of a “humanitarian pause” continue.
How Russia Opened “Humanitarian Windows” in Aleppo
Amid the ongoing battle for Aleppo, Syria’s second-largest city, Russia on Aug. 11 announced a three-hour ceasefire that will be in place on a daily basis starting Thursday.
The creation of “humanitarian windows” is designed to provide conditions for the delivery of medicines, food and essentials to the city.
The decision of the Ministry of Defense of the Russian Federation was made against the background of increasing international pressure on Moscow with the requirement to curtail the military operation and contribute to the resumption of the negotiation process.
As a result of a series of explosions in the resorts of Thailand killed four people.
Several explosions occurred in southern Thailand on Friday morning.
As a result of the attack, four people were killed, 19 were injured.
The epicenter of the explosions fell on the city of Hua Hin.
Among the victims were ten foreigners, citizens of four states, there are no Russians among them.
None of the terrorist groups has yet claimed responsibility for the incident, but the interior Ministry hastened to say that the Islamists were not involved in it.
Several people have already been detained on suspicion of organizing the explosions.
According to preliminary data of the local police, the scale and features of the explosions indicate that they were directed against the leading military.
The attacks took place at popular tourist resorts, including Patong Beach in the Phuket area and the cities of Hua Hin, Trang and Surat Thani.
Since the military junta came to power in 2014, economic growth has fallen from 7.2% (2012) to 2.8% (2015), but tourism has remained one of the few industries to show growth.
In 2016, 14 million people visited the country, which is 1.5 million more than in 2015.
Already detained the first suspects in the preparation and organization of attacks, said police Colonel Chrisana Patanacharoen.
It is too early to talk about the goals, he added, but the interior Ministry of the country "are confident that they are not associated with international extremist groups."
“It’s too early to draw conclusions,” Patanacharoen said.
But we know for sure that these incidents are not directly related to any kind of terrorism, in fact, they are local sabotage, and we are trying to establish the identity of those who were behind them.
The blasts occurred on the birthday of Thailand's Queen Sycrit.
The Thai junta considers protecting the monarchy one of its top priorities, so the incident is likely directed against it.
According to Sithichai police general Srisopacharoenrat, the bombs were detonated remotely within half an hour of each other.
They were hidden inside trees on busy streets filled with dining in restaurants by tourists.
It is already known that one of the four dead was a Thai girl selling street food.
The identity of the other victims is still unknown, but it is known that they are residents of four foreign countries.
According to the Royal Thai Police, among them are four German citizens, three Dutch nationals, two Italian citizens and an Austrian citizen.
There are no Russians among the victims of the explosions, the press service of Rostourism reported.
Local experts also attributed the explosions to the referendum held on August 7, in which 61.4% of the country's population supported the draft of a new constitution.
It was prepared by a constitutional drafting commission appointed by the military junta.
Voters needed to decide whether they supported a system in which the upper house of parliament was fully appointed by the military and had a significant role in electing the country's prime minister.
The new system was adopted and will be tested for the first time in the 2017 parliamentary elections.
We will remind, on May 22, 2014 in Thailand there was a military coup under the leadership of the commander of the army of the country Prayut Chan-Ocha.
This step, he said, was prompted by the ongoing political crisis and the lack of progress in negotiations between the government and the opposition.
The military established the National Peace and Order Council, imposed a curfew and censorship, and dispersed the protesters and the upper house of parliament.
How Bangkok found itself in a state of emergency
The Thai government, led by Prime Minister Yingluck Shinawatra, declared a state of emergency in Bangkok and surrounding provinces in January 2014.
The special regime lasted 60 days.
There were two explosions in Bangkok.
In January 2014, two explosions occurred in downtown Bangkok near the Victory Monument, where one of the main protests took place, in which 28 people were injured, five of them in critical condition.
The explosions were carried out by unknown persons on motorcycles.
Authorities have stepped up security in the capital and mobilized military forces to protect demonstrators.
In Dry Log, the development of conditions began.
As it became known to Kommersant, the government was invited to agree on the draft terms of the auction for the Sukhoi Log gold deposit, while maintaining two key restrictions.
The auction is proposed to prevent companies where 25% and more belong to foreigners, and those applicants whose capital will not be at least 25% of state participation.
Industry participants do not expect the government to rewrite the terms, noting that many players are not at risk of taking on a complex and expensive project.
The auction can be announced in August and held in October.
The Ministry of Natural Resources submitted to the government a draft order and terms of the auction for the largest undeveloped gold deposit in Russia, Sukhoi Log (Irkutsk region, reserves and resources - 130 million ounces), two sources familiar with the situation told Kommersant.
The project was submitted on Wednesday evening, one of them said.
The Ministry of Natural Resources confirmed to Kommersant that the project was submitted to the government.
The representative of the Deputy Prime Minister Alexander Khloponin, who oversees the subsoil use, told Kommersant that the project has not yet been received by the official’s office.
“The auction can be announced in August, immediately after the release of the government order, and taking into account the deadline for the collection of applications of potential participants (at least 45 days), the tender can be held in October,” the ministry said.
According to Kommersant, the project retained two key requirements for potential participants, prescribed in the version that was sent for approval to ministries and federal agencies in July (have Kommersant).
The first is the presence in the capital of applicants of at least 25% of state participation.
The second is the denial of access to the auction for companies under the control of foreign investors, based on the understanding of the Federal Law 57 on foreign investment in strategic companies.
According to the two articles of the Federal Law specified in the draft, as Kommersant already wrote on August 2, companies whose beneficiaries (25% of shares and above) are not tax residents of the Russian Federation or have dual citizenship may not be admitted to the auction.
The government has the right to impose such restrictions, since Sukhoi Log belongs to the subsoil of federal significance (stocks of more than 50 tons of gold).
The Ministry of Natural Resources confirmed that the project “contains restrictions on the admission of foreign companies”, but refused to comment on the details before the government order.
The demand for state participation in the capital of the auction participants was put forward by the Irkutsk region, Kommersant said in December 2015 to the Ministry of Natural Resources and later confirmed by the governor of the region Sergey Levchenko, noting that it was sent to the Ministry of Natural Resources by his predecessor Sergei Eroshchenko, "who had agreements on investment projects with Rostec."
Who lobbied for a restriction on the admission of foreigners, the interlocutors of "Kommersant" do not specify.
“But it is in the spirit of the times: not to give control in the largest gold deposit in Russia against the background of Western sanctions,” says the interlocutor of “Kommersant”, familiar with the preparation of the auction.
On August 1, the head of the Ministry of Natural Resources Sergey Donskoy said that foreigners “can go to the consortium” if the applicants attract them “as a financial structure, technological partners.”
The interlocutors of “Kommersant” consider it unlikely that the government will adjust the conditions.
The main contender for Sukhoi Log in the industry is the consortium of the largest gold miner of the Russian Federation PJSC Polyus, controlled by the son of Suleiman Kerimov Said, and Rostec.
As Kommersant wrote, in July, the partners created the joint venture "SL Gold", where Polyus has 51% of the shares, the structure of Rostec RT-GR - 49%.
Rostec declined to comment, Polyus said Kommersant was “certainly interested in this asset” and had all the necessary competencies and resources for its development.
"But the final decision on the possibility and format of our participation will be made after the conditions are announced," Polyus added.
ALROSA may participate in the auction, but the decision is up to the government of the Russian Federation, sources told Kommersant.
The possibility of participating in the development of the Dry Log was stated by Russian GV Gold and Canadian Kinross, developing assets in Chukotka, while Polymetal and Nordgold, according to Kommersant, are not interested in the asset.
The head of the Union of gold miners of the Russian Federation Sergey Kashuba in December 2015 estimated Kommersant investment in Sukhoi Log at $ 2.5-4 billion.
Most potential applicants are deterred not only by the volume of investment, but also by the complexity of the project: serious additional exploration of reserves and technologies for working with complex ores is needed, the interlocutors of Kommersant in the industry explain.
On the pension market launched the largest deal M&A - "KIT Finance Pension Administrator" launched the process of combining the four controlled NPF.
As a result, on the basis of "Gazfond Pension savings" will be created NPF with savings of about 373 billion rubles.
About the launch of the procedure for combining four pension funds - "KIT Finance", "Promagrofund", "Heritage" and "Gazfond Pension Savings" - yesterday the owner of 100% of the funds of "KIT Finance Pension Administrator" LLC announced.
"The reorganization is carried out in coordination with the Central Bank in compliance with the requirement of non-deterioration of the terms of existing contracts," the company said in a statement.
The association is held on the basis of "Gazfond Pension savings".
As the general director of this NPF Oleg Byaloshytsky notes, the pooling of funds allows solving several tasks: expanding the geography of presence, concentrating resources for development, reducing costs, replicating the best practices of each of the funds and optimizing corporate governance.
According to him, the estimated date for the completion of consolidation is the second quarter of 2017.
As a result of the merger, NPF "Gazfond Pension Savings" will become the largest player in the OPS market.
As of March 31, the volume of pension savings of combining funds exceeded 373 billion rubles.
As follows from the reports on the website of the funds, the beneficiaries of their owner - "KIT Finance Pension Administrator" - are now Anatoly Gavrilenko (through controlled LLC owns 65%) and NPF "Gazfond" (35%).
However, the group itself launched much later competitors.
So, controlled by the group O1 NPF "Future" absorbed "Stalfond" at the beginning of this year.
Currently, this joint NPF joins the funds "Uralsib" and "Russian Standard".
“Unification into a single structure, in addition to reducing costs, is necessary to solve structural problems,” said Nikolay Sidorov, general director of NPF Future.
Active work on the consolidation of funds since April is going on in the pension group "Safmar" - NPF "European", "Education and Science" and "Regionfund" should join the NPF "Safmar" before the end of this year.
In 2017, NPF "Trust" will join them.
"The pooling of funds will give the effect of strengthening control over risks, operational processes and costs," Safmar said in a statement.
A pause in the pooling of funds, which sustained the "KIT Finance Pension Administrator", can be caused by several reasons, experts point out.
Until recently, NPFs could not buy back more than 40% of the volume of infrastructure bonds, in which the group was actively placed.
After the amendments to the resolution of the Central Bank in March this year for a number of issuers that meet the requirements of the regulator, such restrictions no longer exist.
If necessary, the entire issue can be redeemed by one major player, ”says Yuri Nogin, director of the rating group of financial institutions of ACRA.
Several leaders of NPF from the top 15 for assets another possible reason for the pause called the division of spheres of influence and, as a result, personnel appointments in a single fund, which were to be agreed upon by the owners of the group.
Yesterday, Anatoly Gavrilenko was unavailable for comment.
NPF "Gazfond" also did not respond to the request "Kommersant".
Although the consolidation of funds is a labor-intensive and expensive event, at a long distance this decision will be justified.
As the general director of the consulting company Pension Partner Sergey Okolesnov notes, Gazfond Pension Savings has fewer outflows, the accession will stabilize the base of other funds of the group.
At the same time, a more successful experience of NPF "KIT Finance" and "Promagrofund" will be required in building retail sales of OPS, as well as the use of more modern software.
The requirements of the Central Bank to the processes and personnel of the NPF are constantly growing, so it is inexpedient to duplicate the infrastructure on four funds with a single investment policy, says Pavel Mitrofanov, Managing Director for Corporate Ratings at Expert RA.
"The effect of reducing duplicate functions will definitely cover the possible costs of unification," Mitrofanov said.
The cost of combining the four funds Sergey Okolesnov estimates at 30-50 million rubles.
“The cost of maintaining four funds of this size is about 400 million rubles. per year, with the consolidation in the medium term, the budget really cut by half,” said Mr. Okolesnov.
In the Russian rental was released the kindest Disney movie "Pete and his dragon".
The beautiful views of New Zealand, the soothing dragon, the soulful story and country songs are enough to believe in old-fashioned magic again, says Elena Kravtsun.
The frightened baby was picked up by a dragon, who became a human cub and a gentle nurse, and a devoted friend.
Pete calls his friend Elliot, after the puppy from the book of fairy tales, plays catch-up with him and falls asleep in a hug.
Six years later, he, overgrown and in a loincloth, can no longer be distinguished from another clever forest plucker - Mowgli.
In this form, Pete is discovered by a red-haired female huntsman Grace (Bryce Dallas Howard), while Gavin's brigade (Carl Urban), her husband's brother, aggressively plows the forest.
Now she will not only have to believe in the existence of the dragon, but also to help save it.
Pete goes through an accelerated course of "being human" surrounded by idyllic Americans who wear cowboy shirts, a moral code in the heart and smile more dazzlingly than in any advertising.
No character looks or acts too awful for the viewer to really hate or fear.
