The Spiritual Directorate of Muslims (DUM) of Tatarstan refuses to use the Russian language in mosques.
Yesterday, the plenum of the DUM ordered its imams to conduct Friday sermons only in Tatar, in order to force young Tatars to “learn their native language.”
It says it “in no way infringes” on the rights of Muslims of other nationalities.
Some mosques in Kazan complain that up to 60% of parishioners, including foreign students, migrants and Tatars themselves, do not understand the Tatar language.
Imams fear that their sermons in Tatar “will not reach the entire audience.”
Yesterday, the plenum of the DUM of Tatarstan unanimously decided to hold Friday sermons in the mosques of the republic only in the Tatar language.
As stated by the mufti of Tatarstan Kamil Samigullin, this should be an incentive for young Tatars to “learn their native language.”
“For those who say that it is “heavy”, in every large mosque we intend to organize lessons of the Tatar language absolutely free,” said Mr. Samigullin.
He added that "the decision has already entered into force" and today in all mosques the sermon "should already be in the Tatar language."
He recalled that the DUM of Tatarstan publishes the magazine "Shura" with typical sermons in the Tatar language.
An imam who doesn’t speak Tatar well enough “can be thoroughly prepared for them.”
The DUM of Tatarstan unites more than a thousand parishes in all municipalities of the republic.
According to the mufti, Friday sermons are conducted exclusively in the Tatar language in the districts.
At the same time, in Kazan, a number of mosques used primarily Russian.
In particular, as the mufti pointed out, this was practiced in the Burnaev Mosque, Zakabanna and Eniler.
However, Mr. Mukhametshin stressed, the management sets the task for all students to speak both state languages of the republic, regardless of nationality.
"There can be no talk of any infringement of Netatar Muslims," Mukhametshin said, explaining that the sermon itself "is not an obligatory, basic part of prayer."
At the same time, the prayer itself will continue to be read in Arabic, and there will be lectures and lessons in Russian in mosques.
At the same time, Rafik Mukhametshin told Kommersant that there was no serious threat of ousting the Tatar language from mosques.
In addition to Russian and Tatar, other languages, for example, Uzbek or Tajik, according to his information, are not used in sermons in the republic.
The decision of the DUM was actively supported in the executive committee of the World Congress of Tatars (WCT).
Rinat Zakirov, head of the executive committee of the VKT, said: “Mosques are an important part of our national life.”
It would be sad if the Tatar language left this sphere.
He noted that the conduct of sermons only in the Tatar language “the desire of the imams themselves”, but the executive committee of the WCT “consider it correct”.
The imams interviewed by Kommersant, who conducted sermons in Russian, are ready to fulfill the decision of the DUM, but they believe that parishioners will have difficulties in understanding the clergy.
Both Tatars and Russians go to the mosque.
Many do not understand the language.
Of course, they will be bored.
“We will have to rebuild,” says the imam of the Burnaev mosque, Farhat Mavletdinov.
According to him, the sermons in Russian are closer even to many Tatars, because "Russian in schools and kindergartens, on the radio - everywhere initially."
However, he believes that the mosque will be able to continue lessons and lectures in Russian, which are held on other days.
We rely on God.
Allah will show you the way out of this situation,” he concluded.
But about 60% of us do not know the Tatar language.
These are Uzbeks, Tajiks, and Azerbaijanis.
Many foreign students come to us: Africans, Arabs.
“That’s why we switched to Russian for four years,” the imam said.
He believes that in the Tatar language sermons will "reach a narrower circle and will not reach the entire audience."
But we will obey the decision of the plenum.
The result of the sermons will be different.
But time will tell.
“For example, it will only be easier for me, because the Tatar language is my native language,” Gabdulla Galiullin concluded.
The former director of the Federal Penitentiary Service was put on trial
The Moscow Prosecutor’s Office approved the indictment on the criminal case investigated by the SSU of the TFR on the theft of budget funds allocated for the needs of the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia.
Former head of the prison department Alexander Reimer and his deputy, who caused more than 2.7 billion rubles in damage to the Federal Penitentiary Service, will appear before the court.
The Metropolitan Prosecutor's Office sent to the Zamoskvoretsky District Court a criminal case against the former director of the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia Alexander Reimer, his former deputy Nikolai Krivolapov, as well as the director of the Federal State Unitary Enterprise "Center for Information and Technical Support and Communications of the Federal Penitentiary Service" (FSUE CITOS) Viktor Vytorov.
Depending on the role and degree of participation in the commission of crimes, they are accused by the Investigative Committee of Russia under Part 3 of Article 285 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (abuse of official powers, which entailed grave consequences), Part 4 of Article 159 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (fraud committed using their official position, as part of an organized group, on a particularly large scale).
In addition, Krivolapov is charged under Part 1 of Article 222 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (illegal acquisition and storage of ammunition).
According to the TFR, in 2010-2012, these persons fraudulently stole from the state treasury budget funds allocated by the Federal Penitentiary Service to provide the agency with electronic monitoring systems of controlled persons, the so-called electronic bracelets.
To steal budget money, the group members developed a scheme according to which the company controlled by them, FSUE CITOS, with which the relevant state contracts were concluded, produced technical means of control and supervision, including "electronic bracelets", and sold at prices inflated several times.
Despite the fact that FSUE CITOS did not have production equipment, buildings, structures for placing production facilities, allowing to create a complete production cycle of "electronic bracelets", five state contracts worth more than 3.3 billion rubles were concluded between it and the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia.
As a result of this scheme, the accounts of the Samara branch of the FSUE turned out to be more than 2 billion rubles, of which 1.2 billion rubles were stolen.
According to the investigation, more than 140 million rubles. cash received personally Mr. Reimer in his office from one of the accomplices, the criminal case against which is allocated to a separate proceeding.
Nikolai Krivolapov, who participated in the machinations, was found to have ammunition for the award pistol of unknown origin, which allowed him to be charged with an additional charge.
In this case, the volume of which amounted to 133 volumes, the Federal Penitentiary Service filed a claim for compensation for material damage in the amount of 2.7 billion rubles.
Football player Hakan Shukur is suspected of involvement in the coup.
Turkish authorities issued a warrant for the arrest of former football player and then member of parliament Hakan Shukur and conducted searches in two homes of his family.
Turkish football star of the 1990s and early 2000s striker Hakan Shukur is wanted by the authorities in connection with the coup attempt that occurred last month.
The forward, who finished his sports career in 2008, is accused of belonging to an “armed terrorist group”.
We are talking about the Hizmet movement, a society associated with the well-known Turkish religious figure and oppositionist Fethullah Gulen.
It is his President Erdogan considers the organizer of the coup attempt, which occurred on July 15.
Fethullah Gulen lives in the United States, the Turkish authorities are demanding his extradition.
According to local media, today was issued a warrant for the arrest of Hakan Shukur, the police have already conducted searches in two houses that belong to the family of the former football player.
According to investigators, the organization of Fethullah Gulen, in addition to Hakan Shukur himself, included his father.
However, neither the former football player nor his relatives were there.
He and his family now live in the United States.
As a footballer, Hakan Shukur defended the colors of several Turkish clubs and played for the national team of the country.
He spent most of his career at Galatasaray.
The list of foreign clubs includes Italian Torino, Inter and Palermo, as well as English Blackburn.
In fact, he hasn’t played in more than one season.
Hakan Shukur is still the most effective striker of the Turkish national team: he has 112 matches for the national team and 51 goals scored.
In 2013, Hakan Shukur left his deputy post due to the beginning of a corruption investigation around Erdogan’s party and his inner circle.
