Bulgaria shows inflation for the first time in 8 months
Inflation in Bulgaria was 1% monthly in July, according to national statistics.
This is the highest figure for the years (since June 2012) and the first above zero since October last year, when a positive 0.2% was shown.
The average annual inflation measured by the CPI in the last 12 months (August 2015 - July 2016) compared to the previous 12 months (August 2014 - July 2015) was -0.8%.
The consumer price index in July 2016 compared to June 2016 was 101.0%, i.e., monthly inflation was 1.0%.
The inflation rate since the beginning of the year (July 2016 compared to December 2015) was -0.2%, and the annual inflation in July 2016 compared to July 2015 was -0.2%.
In July 2016, compared with the previous month, an increase was observed in the price of the following groups of consumer goods: food and non-alcoholic beverages (1.7%); transport (1.8%); recreation and culture (6.3%); restaurants and hotels (1.2%); other goods and services (0.3%).
Prices decreased for clothing and footwear (2.2%); furniture, household appliances and regular maintenance (0.5%); health (0.1%).
Prices remained at the same level as in the previous month for alcoholic beverages and tobacco; housing, water, electricity, gas and other fuels; communication systems; and education.
Snapchat’s “Anime” Effect Criticized as a Caricature of Asians
Snapchat states that this filter is inspired by the anime, but some reviewers say it is racially tactless.
With the help of the Lens tool, Snapchat allows approximately 150 million users a day to change reality and play with individuality in ways that border on absurdity.
You can turn yourself into a pineapple, a dog or a character to match the picture of Roy Lichtenstein.
Lenses are rough, twisting tools that create more than 30 million corrected selfies a day.
Any mistakes quickly become well-known.
Snapchat lenses have been criticized in the past when they were accused of advertising dark facial skin or encouraging bleached faces as an ideal of beauty.
So when some users were offered a lens this week that gave them slanted eyes, crooked teeth and plump cheeks, some critics saw it as a racist caricature of Asians — “yellow-faced.”
And they wondered whether these recurring contradictions point to a more serious company problem related to diversity.
On Wednesday, reports circulated and followed up with outrage in reports on The Verge and Motherboard, a day after Snapchat said it had removed the feature.
The company commented: The lens was intended as a homage to the anime characters, not as a caricature of Asians.
But experts who know about racism firsthand, the lens reminded offensive stereotypes in action.
Others completely rejected the comparison with anime.
In an email, Grace Sparapani, a Korean-American art student whose photo tweet was actively shared, said the lens was "offensive and at least embarrassing."
She added that "it's hard to argue with the comparison side by side of a very crude caricature of Asians and filter effects.
This shows that the filter is not just yellow-faced, but highly derogatory yellow-faced.
Snapchat isn’t the only company going through these cultural bridges.
American culture seems to be embroiled in a never-ending struggle for diversity and inclusion, from corporate meeting rooms to Hollywood and the devices we all carry with us.
And the huge audience of young people at Snapchat — who are more racially diverse than their older generation — may mean they’re more likely to wait to be understood.
When one of Snapchat’s lenses creates an image that is offensive to the user, then, said 25-year-old Katie Zhu in an interview on Thursday, “this course of events is much more difficult to go unnoticed, as it was before.”
On Thursday, Zhu, a product manager and engineer who works for Medium, decided to delete her Snapchat account and urged others to do the same.
In an article for Medium and in a telephone interview, she said that she believes racial contradictions are the reason for the lack of diversity in recruitment in Snepchat.
Zhu criticized the company’s predominantly white, male-only leadership and ended her article with the hashtag: “DeleteSnapchat.”
As Zhu, who is herself a Chinese-American, wrote: “Either they didn’t have enough non-white people in the state to make such decisions, or they have non-white people working for them, but they don’t hold positions where they can speak safely and openly.”
Other commentators share her point of view, expressing dissatisfaction that Snapchat has not answered most of her questions.
The company does not publish information about the representation of national minorities in its state, emphasizing its status as a private company.
Snapchat declined to discuss the racial origins of its staff on Thursday, but according to a trustee, the company recently hired a recruiter to focus on underrepresented segments of the population and actively try to engage domestic resources.
For her part, Zhu said that she would keep her Snapchat account closed, adding, "I wonder if they actually need more users like us so they can say it's not going to work that way."
