U.S. Central Command officials have altered intelligence reports to present a more optimistic picture of the war against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than is warranted by events on the ground, a congressional commission said in a report released Thursday.
An interim report by the task force set up by Republican chairmen of the House Armed Services Committee, the Intelligence Committee, and the Defense Appropriations Subcommittee found “widespread discontent” among Central Command intelligence analysts, who claim that the leaders were tweaking their assessments of U.S. actions aimed at defeating the Islamic State.
Central Command, known as Centcom, is the main military command in Tampa, Florida, which oversees U.S. military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
“Intelligence documents approved by the top command of Centcom tended to provide a more optimistic portrayal of U.S. counterterrorism activities than confirmed by real data from the scene, and were consistently more optimistic than analysis provided by other intelligence agencies,” the report said.
“What happened at Centcom is unacceptable: When the top leadership is presented with a false analysis, our military suffers,” said Rep. Ken Calvert, a Republican from California.
Problems with leadership at Centcom reach the very top of the organization.
The ten-page report details the shortcomings that constantly arose in 2014 and 2015 in the description and analysis of American actions aimed at training the Iraqi armed forces provided by the Central Command.
While it does not contain definitive evidence that members of the Obama administration’s leadership ordered the reports to be falsified, it does claim that analysts felt that the Centcom leadership was forcing them to present a more optimistic view of the threat from the Islamic State, also known as ISIS or ISIL.
“Throughout the first half of 2015, many of the Central Command’s press releases, statements, and testimony in Congress were significantly more upbeat than actual events,” the report said.
For example, a Centcom official publicly stated that a major military attack aimed at the return of Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq’s second largest city, remains under Islamic State control.
“After months of investigation, that’s for sure,” Rep. Mike Pompeo, a Kansas Republican, said in a statement.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, senior U.S. Central Command intelligence officials forged command documents to downplay the threat posed by ISIS in Iraq.
Republicans set up the task force when they learned that analysts had expressed concern that intelligence about the Islamic State had been falsified.
As the investigation progresses, a report released Thursday will be followed by more detailed data.
An additional, not yet completed investigation of Centcom’s intelligence is being conducted by the Department of Defense’s chief inspector.
Representatives of the Democratic Party on the House Intelligence Committee released their own data on Thursday, which is consistent with some of the findings of the Republican task force.
“Between 2014 and 2015, Centcom created an overly closed procedure for making intelligence assessments of ISIS and Iraq’s security forces,” said Rep. Adam B. Schiff, the party’s top representative on the committee.
The procedure, Schiff said, “has stalled the release of intelligence documents,” damaged the morale of analysts and “does not sufficiently reflect divergent views.”
But Schiff and Democrats say they have found no evidence that the White House has tried to force Centcom analysts to tailor their findings to “a given or political interpretation.”
Preliminary results of the investigation of the Congress were presented on Tuesday by the portal The Daily Beast.
Last August, The New York Times reported on the existence of an investigation by the chief inspector of the Pentagon, opened after complaints by Centcom analysts.
Lieutenant Commander Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement that the Department of Defense would not comment on the congressional report while the inspector general’s investigation is ongoing.
But he said “experts sometimes disagree on the treatment of complex data, and intelligence agencies and the Department of Defense welcome a healthy dialogue on these vital national security topics.”
The implications of the investigation go beyond the question of whether the US-led bombing in Iraq and Syria is reaching its goal (as more and more Defense Department officials now claim).
But last year’s statements cast doubt on whether President Obama can rely on the Central Command to provide truthful assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis points.
Criticism of Islamic State intelligence echoes a debate more than a decade ago, when Centcom intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker wrote a research article claiming that the administration of President George W. Bush, in protest of many analysts, had come out in support of a small number of troops in Iraq and had not thought about what would follow the 2003 invasion.
Hooker also played a key role in the protest sparked by intelligence on the Islamic State.
Last year, officials said, Hooker’s team concluded that despite public statements to the contrary, airstrikes on Islamic State-owned refineries had not led to a significant deterioration in the terrorist group’s financial standing because it had built temporary refineries to sell oil on the black market.
But the opening was not distributed outside Central Command, the Times reported in September.
The then Centcom commander, General Lloyd J. Austin III, was criticized last year after testimony in the Senate that many MPs deemed overly optimistic about the war.
General Austin resigned in April and was replaced in Central Command by Gen. Joseph L. Votel.
