In the midst of the frenzy of the Olympic Games - "zen" of jumping on the trampoline
No matter where you are, no matter what time it is, this is the Olympics.
Events in Rio de Janeiro seem to be constant and inevitable, it is a mad combination of competition and aspiration.
As if the Olympic flame itself is that burning torch that is transmitted from archer to swimmer, to gymnast, to triathlete.
You can’t turn on the TV, read the newspaper, or overhear your neighbors taking turns in the café without hearing about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky, or the feud between Michael Phelps and Chad de Clos.
And then there's Logan Dooley.
Dooley, a first-time Olympian with dimples on his cheeks, could well be among those celebrities shown in prime time promoted by sponsors and life-affirming commercials if he were a swimmer, gymnast, or even a fencer.
But 28-year-old Dooley from the city of Lake Forest in California is fighting for gold in the Olympic jumping competitions on the trampoline.
The Olympic flame does not cover all events in the same way.
Further from the center, partly in the shade, there are those sports that are not universally recognized: air pistol shooting, archery, badminton, taekwondo.
Brass will always be with us, his long reign.
But if I am allowed to speak timidly in defense of my personal preference, let me draw your attention to the modest charm of the trampoline jumps.
Although trampoline jumping has been an Olympic sport since 2000, when it debuted at the Sydney Games, it has received so little recognition in the past 16 years that many people I interviewed were not aware that it was an Olympic sport at all.
This may be regional ignorance.
Although the United States sent athletes to compete, they never won medals in the trampoline jumps, and their athletes did not reach the finals until 2012.
Chinese and Russians tend to share male awards, while Chinese and Canadians share female awards.
Dong Dong of China and Rosie McLennan of Canada will defend their London gold medals this year.
But trampoline jumps have the charm of an outsider, in particular because for the unenlightened ear it is more likely to be associated with a circus college than with the Olympic Games.
Here I must confess that I am not an expert, but only a down-to-earth enthusiast.
They do have comic potential — it’s a caricature of never-ending jumps — but also the grace of gymnastics and diving, the two sports they mostly combine.
The word trampoline comes from the Spanish word "el trampoljn", meaning "springboard for jumping into the water".
Candidates to win jump on a giant trampoline, taking off into the air for almost 30 feet, and must perform a series of acrobatic stunts (turns, folds and flips) before finally landing on their feet.
They are assessed according to performance, complexity and "flight time", according to the official program of the Olympic Games.
Thirty-two athletes from 17 countries, 16 men and 16 women, will compete in Rio.
The most common Olympic course is forward.
Candidates for the medal must go further, faster, higher and higher in the pursuit of gold, sometimes to the finish line, and sometimes back and forth, back and forth across the field.
They aim not only for the finish line or the starting wall, but also, in front of the cameras, for another tantalizing milestone: a world or Olympic record.
This persistent aspiration is noble, worthy of admiration, even fanatical - and it is enough to make even the viewer cry.
But I think it’s a bit exhausting watching the games.
His trampoline jumps give him a break.
The direction of the trampoline is up.
Moving forward is not the goal.
He or she jumps, seems weightless, like an astronaut, flying up, then down, then effortlessly up again.
And they certainly do not do without competition or difficulties, but throughout the program there is no crazy zeal for the finish line, there are no long jumps, only a wonderful, elegant disappearance of time and gravity.
This is the closest Olympic sport to Zen.
The women's qualifying competition and then the final will be held on Friday afternoon, broadcast at 1 pm Eastern European time; men's on Saturday, also at 1 pm.
NBC will broadcast the finals as part of a daytime program starting at 2:00 p.m. on both days.
In the midst of the Olympic madness, a calm, beautiful moment is expected, which can be easily seen in a common landfill.
And if the rise in consciousness can be achieved only by subjecting male athletes to coveted views and objectifications — as the Wall Street Journal recently suggested male gymnasts from the United States — Dooley is just waiting for his new admiring crowd of fans.
"Generation Protests" in Ethiopia, a longtime U.S. ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators demanding political change in Ethiopia have faced fierce opposition from the government.
Eyewitnesses say dozens of protesters were fatally injured during clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia really on the verge of a split?
Over the past decade, it has been one of Africa’s most stable countries, a staunch ally of the West with a booming economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have shaken the country, spreading to an increasing number of its territories.
In the last week alone, thousands of people have taken to the streets to demand radical political change.
Human rights advocates say the government’s response has been brutal.
Eyewitnesses claimed that police officers shot and killed dozens of unarmed demonstrators.
Video footage from the protest sites, allegedly taken late last year or earlier this year, shows security officers beating young men with sticks when they were placed with their hands against the wall.
The highest United Nations human rights official now calls for a thorough investigation.
“It’s always been difficult to keep this country from collapsing, and it’s going to be even harder,” said Rashid Abdi, head of the Horn of Africa project at the International Crisis Research Group.
Ethiopia is Africa’s second most populous country after Nigeria, and its stability is maintained by the West.
U.S. military and intelligence agencies are working closely with Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats in the region, especially Somalia, and virtually no country in Africa receives such support from the West.
Ethiopia’s economy is growing at an impressive rate.
Its infrastructure has improved significantly - there is even a new commuter train in the capital Addis Ababa.
And its streets are usually quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia was hardly a model of democracy - human rights organizations constantly mention government repression - opposition in the territory of the state was suppressed, due to the fact that dissidents were actually silenced.
Many of them were exiled, imprisoned, killed or exiled to remote deserts.
But that could change.
“If people are constantly being repressed and left with no option but to protest, there will be an uprising,” said Seyoum Teshome, a lecturer at a university in central Ethiopia.
All young people are protesting.
The generation is protesting.
Complaints range from land use to the seizure of power by a government coalition.
After last year’s widely criticized election, the government party and its allies have completely supplanted the opposition and now control 100 percent of Parliament.
At the same time, tensions are rising along the border with Eritrea; fighting for this uncertain, contested border claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less destroyed in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to take advantage of the unrest and rearm.
A number of factors explain why bitter feelings, simmering in the depths of the soul for several years, flare up now.
The first, seemingly harmless: smartphones.
Only in the last couple of years, a large number of Ethiopians have been able to communicate on social networks, as cheap smartphones have become commonplace, and Internet service has become better.
Even when the government shuts down Facebook and Twitter, as it often does, especially during protests, many people still find it possible to communicate through proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that was how they organized the protests.
The second is that there is more solidarity between Oromo and Amhara, the two largest Ethiopian ethnic groups.
Oromo and Amhara are not natural allies.
For centuries, Amhara from Ethiopia’s predominantly Christian highlands have thrived in politics and business, exploiting Oromo, many of whom are Muslim and live in low-lying areas.
But that's changing, too.
"We will act together under a single principle," said Mulatu Gemezu, leader of Oromo.
The largest protests took place in Amhara and Oromo districts.
Many of Amhara and Oromo feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which makes up about 6 percent of the population and which controls military and intelligence services, trade, and politics.
The third cause of unrest is the loss of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Prime Minister of Ethiopia for 17 years, until his death from an unknown illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could foresee danger.
Analysts say he was especially adept at recognizing the first signals of discontent and used scouts to obtain data and neutralize opponents.
“The current regime lacks common sense,” said Abdi, a conflict analyst.
Ethiopia's new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalen, appeared out of nowhere and took Meles' place.
Unlike Meles, who was from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is a Southerner.
Analysts say he does not have the trust of the Tigray-controlled security services.
Many fear that this will lead to more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such unrest was in 2005, after thousands of people protested what analysts said were apparently elections that the government froze and then faked the results.
During the ensuing repression, many Protestants were killed, albeit in smaller numbers than in recent months, and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts expressed appreciation for Ethiopia’s leaders’ visionary infrastructure development, such as the new long-distance train and significant progress in the fight against poverty.
But it is obvious that this has not stopped the growth of internal discontent with the Ethiopian government.
And it takes on a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, a city in Amhar, attacked businesses owned by Tigray, and anti-Tigra hatred on social media is becoming all-encompassing.
Analysts say the protesters are putting the United States and other Western allies in an awkward position.
The U.S. government has used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned flights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently announced that it has closed that base.
On the one hand, it is clear that the West wants to support democracy, but on the other hand, it does not want its ally to lose strength in an already unstable region.
“And it will be hard to get through this tightrope,” Abdi said.
