Gilead will reimburse the costs of advocacy services during a dispute over a patent for hepatitis C with Merck
Gilead Sciences Inc. has the right to recover the costs of legal services it has incurred in connection with the dispute over a patent for a hepatitis C drug with the drug manufacturer Merck & Co Inc., a federal district judge ruled.
In June, Gilead was released from paying $200 million in damages for violating two of Merck's patents relating to Gilead drugs, sales leaders Sovaldi and Harvoni, after a U.S. judge found a number of violations by Merck, including lying under oath and other unethical acts.
In a court filing on Thursday, U.S. federal district court judge Beth Labson Freeman said Gilead was entitled to reimbursement of costs incurred in challenging the lawsuit.
Merck is trying to catch up with Gilead, which dominates the market for a new generation of hepatitis C drugs that can cure more than 90 percent of patients with liver disease.
The case took place in 2013, when Gilead and Merck sued each other, claiming their rights to the laboratory work underlying sofosbuvir, the active ingredient in Gilead drugs.
