Clinton earned $10.75 million in 2015 and paid a 34.2 percent federal tax rate
Hillary Clinton on Friday released her 2015 tax returns, which showed that the Democratic presidential candidate and her husband had $10.75 million in income this year and paid an effective federal tax rate of 34.2 percent.
In 2015, the Clintons received $1 million in charitable contributions, mostly to the Clinton Foundation, former President Bill Clinton received about $5.3 million in speaking fees, and the former Secretary of State claimed $3 million in revenue from publisher Simon & Schuster for her book about her tenure in the State Department.
Potential Vice President Clinton, U.S. Senator Tim Kane of Virginia, along with his wife Anna Holton, released tax returns for 10 years.
In 2015, they paid an effective federal tax rate of 20.3 percent.
“Hillary Clinton and Tim Kane continue to set the standard for financial transparency,” Clinton campaign adviser Jennifer Palmieri said in a statement.
In stark contrast, Donald Trump hides behind fake excuses and breaks his past promises to release his tax returns.
It is common for U.S. presidential candidates to publish their tax returns, although the law does not require them to do so.
New York businessman Trump and his lawyers called the audit of the State tax service as the reason for his refusal to disclose their tax returns.
"Your move," Clinton campaign adviser Ian Sams tweeted, referring to the Democratic candidate's declarations.
On Thursday, Trump’s special adviser, Michael Cohen, told CNN that he would not allow Trump to release them before the inspections are over.
Critics of Trump, including Republican presidential candidate Mitt Romney and other fellow Republicans, said his refusal raises questions about his condition, his charitable contributions, his business dealings and other ties, including with Russia.
Clinton seized on the issue and released an online video on Friday that focused on prominent Republicans urging Trump to release tax returns.
On Thursday, she raised the issue during a speech on the economy in Michigan.
“He refuses to do what every single presidential candidate has done for decades: release their tax returns,” she told the crowd.
The Politico newspaper reported that Trump paid no or almost no taxes in two years in the 1990s, and a business columnist for the New York Times on Friday quoted many tax lawyers and accountants who believe that perhaps things are still going on.
Federal tax rates have been the subject of controversy in the presidential election.
Clinton supported a rule named after billionaire investor Warren Buffett that would guarantee that people earning more than $1 million a year would pay a tax rate of at least 30 percent.
President Barack Obama also supported the proposal.
At a meeting with Clinton last week in Omaha, Nebraska, Buffett, whose conglomerate Berkshire Hathaway is based there, invited Trump to meet and exchange tax returns.
Buffett said he too is under scrutiny by the IRS, and that Trump is “afraid” not of the tax collection agency, but of voters.
Clinton’s campaign released tax returns until 2007.
The Clintons, who now live in Chappaqua, New York, paid an average federal tax rate of about 32 percent from 2007 to 2014 and an effective aggregate tax rate of about 40.5 percent.
The 2015 Clinton Declaration showed that, unlike most Americans, only $100 of their income came from salaries.
Their main investment was a low-cost index mutual fund, and the Clintons reported dividends and capital gains of $109,000.
Additional reporting by Kevin Drobo; editor Jonathan Oatis
Condoms with Chili Powder and Fireworks Increase Protection for Tanzanian Elephants
Environmentalists in Tanzania are using an unconventional way to prevent elephants from wandering into communities — throwing condoms filled with chili powder into them.
The method proved effective, and the Honeyguide Foundation, which came up with the idea a few years ago, along with the U.S. Committee on Nature Conservation, took over its promotion, training volunteers in villages in northern Tanzania to use a nonviolent, four-step way to protect their homes and crops without harming animals.
Previously, many used spears to protect themselves.
Friday is World Elephant Day, dedicated to the protection of animals.
"Since we invented the toolkit ... we have seen a change in attitudes within these communities, resulting in much greater confidence that they will be able to keep elephants out of their fields without harming elephants," said Honeyguide executive director Damian Bell in a statement.
The first two steps are to light the torch in front of the elephant and signal with the horn.
If he failed to scare away, they throw the so-called “chili cloud”.
Chili powder, mixed with soil, is placed with a clap in the condom, and its end is twisted, only the wick remains outside.
When ignited, the condom bursts with a bang, spraying fine dust of chili powder into the air.
One breath is usually enough to turn the elephant in the other direction.
The ultimate measure is a launcher that fires Roman candles into the air, producing a loud, bright explosion.
