The future of the Portland steel plant is under threat due to the termination of the electricity contract
The future of the Portland aluminum plant in Victoria — as well as the jobs of hundreds of workers — is under threat due to the fact that the electric power company that supplies the plant, according to one of the plant owners, is going to terminate the supply contract: it is planned that all supply contracts will be terminated.
The move follows a decision earlier this year by the Victorian government not to extend subsidies to support the plant’s operation.
A fixed subsidy of 20 years expires in November.
Up to 2,000 jobs could be at risk at Alcoa’s Portland plant.
As many as 2,000 jobs, directly and indirectly, could be at risk as a result of any closure.
There may also be additional indirect effects, as the steel plant consumes about 10 percent of all electricity produced in Victoria.
In 2014, Alcoa closed a steel plant in Point Henry, which led to the closure of the Anglesey power plant last year.
Portland-based steelmaker Alcoa is losing money and risking closure.
These actions were the result of reflections on the future of the plant, which have been going on for several years, initially due to the strong position of the Australian dollar, and later - due to the price of the plant's products.
AGL, which supplies a large aluminum plant with electricity from its Loy Yang A power plant in Latrobe Valley, said it expects the other three owners to also take steps to terminate the contracts.
The controlling share of the plant is owned by the joint venture of Alcoa and Alumina, while the Chinese company CITIC and the Japanese company Marubeni Corp own smaller shares.
“AGL expects the Portland facility to continue operating, meaning that the physical demand for electricity from the steel plant will not stop,” she said.
According to AGL, these contracts are the so-called “hedged contracts”, which were supposed to come into force in November 2016.
The contracts have a 12-month termination period, so they will actually end in 2017.
“Accordingly, AGL still expects these contracts to generate their share of revenue in fiscal year 2017,” the electricity company said.
Any potential impact on AGL’s earnings from fiscal 2018 onwards is currently limited to forecasts for a strong futures market for wholesale electricity prices.
AGL said it had already reduced the amount of contracts in its statements by $187 million in view of the "coming termination".
