Anyone with information about the incident on Thursday near the Morge should call the police on 021 644 83 46 or 021 644 44 44.
NASA's climate model: Venus was once habitable
Venus may have once been habitable, according to estimates from NASA’s new climate model.
Scientists from the Nasov Space Research Institute Goddard developed a model for the study of the past of Venus, using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climatologists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, with its hot, waterless surface and atmosphere saturated with carbon dioxide, could ever have conditions similar to Earth’s.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus' low rotation rate is due to its dense atmosphere.
But the latest simulation suggests that Venus may have had a rarefied atmosphere similar to Earth’s and still rotated slowly.
The model also examined the topography of early Venus.
The planet likely had more arid regions than Earth, but once it had enough water and enough geographic variability to create the conditions for life and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited from the sun, which was 30 percent dimmer.
“According to the GISS model, Venus’ slow rotation exposes its daytime side to the sun for almost two months at a time,” GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio explained in a press release.
This warms the planet’s surface and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds acting as an umbrella protecting the planet’s surface from substantial solar heat.
The result is average climate temperatures that, surprisingly, are a few degrees colder than they are today on Earth.
The model shows the history of Venus, similar to the development previously assumed by experts in the study of planets.
Although Venus may have once been habitable, it has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation for several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated and its water vapor was burned by ultraviolet radiation.
When its hydrogen evaporated, only a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide remained with a deadly greenhouse effect — that is, Venus as we know it today.
The researchers shared the results of their new climate model of Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
