Kepler measures the rotation rates of stars in the Pleiades cluster
The latest mission of the space telescope Kepler helped astronomers to collect the most complete catalog of the rotation speeds of the stars that make up the Pleiades cluster.
The new data help astronomers understand why stars in the cluster rotate at different speeds, as well as how periods of rotation correlate with the formation of planets.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between the mass of the star, its age and even the history of its solar system," said Louise Riball, a researcher at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at the California Institute of Technology.
The Pleiades cluster is 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster are now only reaching maturity; they were born about 125 million years ago.
They're spinning as fast as they'll never be again.
At their peak rotation speeds, these maturing stars eject large amounts of stellar wind.
Traveling through the magnetic fields of stars, these winds have a inhibitory effect on stars.
As a star ages, its rotation rate begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotational speed of each star by tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable starspots, such as sunspots.
The latest catalog of rotation speeds suggests that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Riball compares stars to dancers: larger ones make pirouettes slower than smaller ones.
"In the Pleiades, we see that those that rotate slowly are usually more massive, whereas those that rotate faster are usually very light stars," Riball said.
Since the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing the properties of stars with rotation speeds.
"The Pleiades star cluster provides a starting point for theoretical models of the rotation of stars, both younger and older," Riball said.
We still want to learn a lot about how, where and why stars slow down their rotation and hang their “dancing shoes” to the nail, figuratively speaking.
Riball and her colleagues detailed their latest analysis of Pleiades' rotational speeds in three new papers that will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
