Trapped between Angola and South Africa, Namibia has suffered greatly during the long struggle against apartheid.
However, since independence from South Africa in 1990, this country of 2.4 million people has made tremendous strides, especially in the last few years.
The main reason for Namibia's success is that the government pays great attention to education.
While people in developed countries take for granted free primary and secondary education, in many poor countries, secondary and even primary schools require tuition fees.
Moreover, Governments are often advised to introduce training fees to “recover costs”.
In Namibia, however, primary education is free of charge.
Moreover, since 2015, secondary education has also become free.
The country’s authorities are also actively working in other important areas.
Efforts to eradicate malaria have reduced the number of annual cases by 97% over the past ten years.
Contrary to the international trend of rising inequality, it is declining in Namibia.
Compared to 1993, the Gini coefficient, the standard measure of income inequality, dropped by 15 points.
Then, 23 years ago, this figure was one of the highest in the world.
The poverty rate fell from 69 per cent in 1993 to less than 30 per cent.
The number of people living in extreme poverty (less than $1.90 a day) also declined, from nearly 53% to less than 23%.
Namibia also has the highest freedom of speech rating in Africa, according to Reporters Without Borders.
The country was far ahead of the United States and other wealthy nations.
In addition, the country has a favorable rating - one of the highest in Africa - in the Corruption Perceptions Index, which is made up of human rights activists from Transparency International.
Even now, as commodity prices fall, Namibia has managed to maintain a high growth rate.
At the same time, the ratio of debt to GDP is about 25%, which is less than 1/3 of the debt level in the United States and most European countries.
Of course, Namibia has some problems.
The unemployment rate, at least according to traditional valuation methods, is still quite high - almost 28%.
And, like other countries in the region, Namibia has a high incidence of HIV/AIDS - almost 17% of the population is infected.
The World Bank estimates that Namibia is among the upper-middle-income countries, but the authorities insist that their country is actually a developing country.
Namibia certainly faces some of the difficulties inherent in underdeveloped economies.
The state has to develop a very large and dry country with a small population.
On the territory of the country in the deserts live isolated nomadic tribes of hunter-gatherers, which in one way or another should be integrated into modern society, without losing their identity.
Integration of people who a quarter of a century ago were on the periphery of the world economy is not an easy task for any country.
For Namibia, this is even more difficult: just like any other country in the world, it faces the effects of climate change.
However, Namibia did not think to give up, the country is solving the problems facing it.
Almost immediately after independence, the authorities began to create a diversified economy and a cohesive society.
It is noteworthy that competing political factions came together to work for the common good.
Indeed, Namibia provides cheap medical care not only to its own citizens, but also to its neighbours.
About 15-20% of visitors to health facilities in northern Namibia are Angolan citizens.
No one in Namibia is talking about building a wall that would separate the country from its poor and corrupt neighbors.
Namibians realized that their neighbors were not chosen, and therefore decided not to conflict with them, but to cooperate - to share scarce water resources, take part in regional medical projects, encourage investment and student exchange.
In addition, the Namibian government has rightly judged that rich natural resources can easily become a curse, contributing to the enrichment of the few at the expense of the many.
The authorities understand that the revenues from Namibia’s natural resources need to be invested in infrastructure and production facilities.
They are also aware that it would be irresponsible not to seek to maximize profits from the sale of a country’s resources, and are reviewing investment laws and production contracts to make sure this is the case.
Transparency is crucial to this process, which is why the government’s strong support for free speech is so important.
As the head of state Hage Geingob noted, the media often say what he does not like.
But after fighting for freedom from apartheid in South Africa, Namibia must defend the freedoms it has gained, the president says.
Not all of Namibia's key resources are exhausted.
Some - such as fishing - are renewable, and the government is making every effort to preserve and strengthen them.
Every year more than a million foreign tourists visit the country.
Namibia shows that even those countries that begin with serious shortcomings - racism, colonialism, inequality and underdevelopment - can embark on a path to shared prosperity.
Its achievement deserves international recognition and imitation.
Many have heard of the "Golden Varna" - the oldest gold objects created by man (4600 - 4200 BC).
Perhaps it was the loudest archaeological sensation of the 1970s: in Bulgaria, during the excavations of the Varna necropolis, a fantastic number of gold artifacts was found - more than three thousand with a total weight of 6 kilograms.
Only one burial site, known as Grave No. 43, recovered 990 gold objects with a total weight of more than 1.5 kg.
However, the official status of the oldest gold in the world may soon move to a nondescript-looking bead, found by archaeologists in July of this year.
And again in Bulgaria - in a prehistoric settlement known as Tell Yunazite.
Unlike Varna, a port city, Tell Yunacite is located far from the sea, near the village of Yunacite of the Pazardzhik district.
The bead is a golden stripe rolled into a ring.
Yavor Boyadzhiyev, the head of the excavations at Tell Yunazit, dated the find to 4600 BC and stated that it is at least 200 years older than Varna gold.
The treasures of Varna, we recall, date from about the same period, 4600-4200 BC.
Technologies that allow to date metal with perfect accuracy do not currently exist.
How do you know which gold is older?
Apparently, Professor Boyadzhiev knows more than he told Reuters: “I am quite sure that Yunazit’s gold is older than Varna’s gold.”
This is a find of extreme importance: it looks like a tiny object, but it is large enough to take its rightful place in history.
In an interview with Reuters, Boyadzhiyev said that in the near future scientists will analyze the composition of the metal, as well as re-examine and more thoroughly the archaeological layer where the gold artifact was found.
This will help to date the bead with the highest possible accuracy.
The location also explains a lot.
Tell Yunacite is a famous settlement, even if you have never heard of it.
At present, Tell Yunacite is considered the oldest "city" in Europe.
Tell was founded by descendants of people who migrated to Europe from Anatolia (modern Turkey) in the 7th millennium BC.
Over the next centuries, metal processing developed rapidly in this region, from the development of the first metallurgical skills to the creation of a full-fledged industry.
In the national historiography for this archaeological community has a special name: Balkan-Carpathian metallurgical province.
In the 5th millennium BC, urban-type settlements began to appear around metalworking centers.
Now they are called the oldest cities in Europe.
Of these, Tell Yunacite is perhaps the most ancient, as artifacts from 4900 BC have been found here.
I would call Tell Yunacite a prototype of the modern city, although it is a very ancient settlement, even compared to Mesopotamia.
“This place is a thousand years older than Sumer,” says Boyadzhiev, referring to the generally accepted opinion that urban culture originated in southern Mesopotamia - modern Iraq.
There arose the first cities in the usual sense of the word.
The excavations of Tell Yunazite have been conducted since 1976.
During this time, archaeologists have excavated almost 12 hectares, which is about a third of the estimated total area of the settlement.
The remains of the fortress wall were found, which once reached three meters in height.
Little remains of the houses and workshops, but archaeologists clearly distinguish streets, public buildings, urban dense buildings, the "business center" and residential outskirts.
Tell Yunazite is often called the "Bird City": dozens of clay figures of birds were found here.
All birds are depicted at rest, hence the assumption that they were not decorative objects, but an object of local worship.
The "bird city" was destroyed around 4100 BC - possibly by Indo-European tribes coming from the northeast.
Nomads had no cities, but horses and weapons.
The three-meter walls did not stop them.
Archaeologists have found obvious signs of a brutal massacre: inside the houses were found the remains of old people, women and children with traces of wounds inflicted by battle axes.
New findings and new facts appear annually, changing the usual ideas about the ancient history of mankind.
Bulgarian archaeologists are increasingly talking not about individual cultures, but about the “lost” first civilization of Europe, which originated in the Balkans.
A powerful incentive in the search for this civilization was the “gold of Varna”, found relatively recently, in 1972.
It is logical that Varna’s gold opulence should have been preceded by something like a tiny gold bead created in the Yunazit Tell.
